Storage Drivers:
-----------------
Let's explore Docker Storage Drivers â€” a foundational component of how Docker manages image layers and container filesystems.

âœ… What are Docker Storage Drivers?
A storage driver is how Docker reads and writes container data to disk â€” including images, layers, and container writable layers.

It handles:
   --> Layering of images
   --> Copy-on-write operations
   --> Managing the container's file system

ðŸ”¥ Common Docker Storage Drivers:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Driver           | Platform                  | Notes                                     |
| ---------------- | ------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| **overlay2**     | Most modern Linux distros | Default for most recent Docker versions   |
| **aufs**         | Older Ubuntu versions     | Deprecated, replaced by `overlay2`        |
| **devicemapper** | RHEL/CentOS               | Deprecated as well                        |
| **btrfs**        | Btrfs filesystem required | Advanced snapshotting                     |
| **zfs**          | ZFS needed                | Robust, high-performance                  |
| **vfs**          | Any                       | No layering, mostly for testing/debugging |

âœ… How to Check Which Driver Docker Is Using
Run:

docker info | grep Storage

Example output:
Storage Driver: overlay2

ðŸ” How overlay2 Works
    --> Uses Linux OverlayFS.
    --> Combines lower (read-only) and upper (read-write) layers into a single unified view.
    --> Efficient and fast for most workloads.

âœ… How to Specify a Storage Driver (if needed)
Set it in Docker's daemon config file:

ðŸ“„ /etc/docker/daemon.json
{
  "storage-driver": "overlay2"
}

Then restart Docker:
sudo systemctl restart docker

ðŸ§  Real-World Tips
    --> Always prefer overlay2 unless you have specific reasons.
    --> Avoid switching drivers on a running system with containers â€” it can corrupt data or make images unusable.
    --> Use vfs only for testing, as it doesn't support layered images.

âœ… Storage Driver & Image Layers
    Each Docker image is made of multiple layers. The storage driver:
      --> Combines these into one unified filesystem.
      --> Manages changes (write layer) per container.

ðŸ”§ Example: Inspect Layer Paths (Linux)
      --> ls /var/lib/docker/overlay2
       
Youâ€™ll see folders for each layer, with contents like:
      --> diff/ â€” actual files
      --> merged/ â€” what the container sees
      --> work/ â€” used by OverlayFS
